    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1429962714451-bb934ecdc4ec?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>In an announcement that sent Nigerian social media into a frenzy unprecedented even by the standards of Afrobeats' global ascendancy, Davido (David Adeleke) and Wizkid (Ayodeji Ibrahim Balogun) posted a joint video at midnight Friday announcing a collaborative studio album — titled "Lagos to the World" — scheduled for release on June 21, 2026, alongside a 28-date joint world tour spanning Lagos, Accra, London, New York, Toronto, Paris, Dubai and São Paulo.</p><p>The announcement, which simultaneously broke both artists' Instagram record for engagements within one hour, ended a decade of rivalry, public shade-throwing and fan-war tribalism that has divided Nigerian music followers into Wizkid FC and 30BG factions. The video showed both artists in the studio in Lagos with Grammy-winning producer P2J, laughing and embracing, with the caption "This one's for Nigeria. This one's for Africa. This one's for the world."</p><p>Streaming platforms were temporarily overwhelmed as fans rushed to pre-save the album. Spotify Nigeria temporarily crashed, and Apple Music reported its highest Nigerian traffic spike since Burna Boy's Grammy win. Industry insiders estimate pre-release hype alone has made "Lagos to the World" the most commercially valuable Afrobeats release in history before a single note has been publicly heard.</p><p>The Lagos concert, scheduled for June 21 at the refurbished Teslim Balogun Stadium, sold out in 11 minutes — tickets priced from ₦30,000 to ₦3 million. Tour promoters Live Nation confirmed additional dates are being added in response to demand.</p><p>President Tinubu posted a congratulatory video, calling the collaboration "a moment of national unity through art that money cannot buy."</p>`,
