    id:"n1", category:"Nigeria", categorySlug:"nigeria",
    headline:"Lagos Mega Bridge Project Inaugurated: 4.5km Span Cuts Cross-Island Journey From 90 to 12 Minutes",
    snippet:"Governor Sanwo-Olu commissioned the completed Lagos Outer Ring Road Bridge on Saturday, a ₦380 billion infrastructure project that reshapes movement across Lagos Island and the mainland.",
    time:"2 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1503387762-592deb58ef4e?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Governor Babajide Sanwo-Olu commissioned the completed Lagos Outer Ring Road Bridge — a 4.5-kilometre, 10-lane bridge connecting Eko Atlantic City to Lagos Island at a cost of ₦380 billion — in what his administration is calling the most transformative infrastructure investment in Lagos history. The bridge reduces the journey between Lekki Phase 1 and Lagos Island from a typical 90-minute ordeal to approximately 12 minutes, transforming the economic geography of Africa's largest city.</p><p>The project, funded through a combination of Lagos State bonds, World Bank infrastructure credit and private sector contributions from Access Bank, Dangote Group and Zenith Bank, employed over 12,000 construction workers at its peak and used more than 180,000 tonnes of locally produced steel — a significant boost to Nigeria's domestic steel industry.</p><p>For the estimated 4 million Lagos residents who make the cross-island journey daily, the opening is a dramatic quality-of-life improvement. Estate agents reported within hours of the inauguration that property prices in Lekki, Ajah and Sangotedo had already begun rising, anticipating the surge in demand from workers who can now live further from Lagos Island without sacrificing hours in traffic.</p><p>President Tinubu attended the inauguration, calling the bridge "proof that Nigeria can build world-class infrastructure when political will matches technical capacity." The Federal Government announced it would use the Lagos bridge model as a template for similar projects in Port Harcourt, Kano and Enugu.</p><p>However, critics noted that the bridge primarily benefits residents of upscale Lekki estates while Lagos's failing public transport system, overwhelmed drainage and crumbling inner-city roads continue to affect the majority of the city's 22 million residents.</p>`,
