    id:"n2", category:"Nigeria", categorySlug:"nigeria",
    headline:"Borno Solar Grid Powers 2 Million Homes as Governor Zulum Declares Energy Independence",
    snippet:"Governor Zulum inaugurated the $240M Borno Solar Energy Project on Saturday, providing 24/7 electricity to 2 million households in communities that previously had no grid access.",
    time:"5 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1509391366360-2e959784a276?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Borno State Governor Babagana Zulum declared "energy independence" for his state on Saturday as the $240 million Borno Solar Energy Project went fully live, connecting 2 million households — approximately 85% of the state's population — to reliable solar-generated electricity for the first time. The project, the largest off-grid solar installation in sub-Saharan Africa, was funded through a combination of World Bank grants, Islamic Development Bank loans and direct state investment.</p><p>For communities in Borno's rural local government areas that spent years under the shadow of Boko Haram's insurgency, electricity represents not just convenience but safety, economic opportunity and dignity. School attendance in newly electrified communities jumped 34% in pilot areas where the grid went live three months ago, according to Borno State Education Ministry data.</p><p>The project's 180 megawatt capacity is distributed across 3,200 mini-grid installations and 680,000 individual solar home systems, providing power that operates 24 hours daily regardless of cloud cover, thanks to large-scale battery storage infrastructure. The technology was supplied by Chinese firm CCECC and installed by a workforce that was 80% drawn from Borno State residents.</p><p>Governor Zulum — who has become one of Nigeria's most admired state executives for his hands-on approach to post-insurgency reconstruction — said the project was "the first step toward making Borno State the renewable energy capital of West Africa." He announced plans for a second phase targeting industrial energy supply for small businesses.</p><p>Federal Minister of Power Adebayo Adelabu attended the inauguration and said the project would inform the Federal Government's accelerated rural electrification programme, with similar projects planned for Zamfara, Kebbi and Yobe states.</p>`,
