    id:"n3", category:"Nigeria", categorySlug:"nigeria",
    headline:"WHO Confirms Deadly New Disease Outbreak in Plateau State — 34 Dead, 200 Quarantined",
    snippet:"The World Health Organization has confirmed a novel haemorrhagic fever outbreak in Plateau State with a 28% fatality rate. NCDC has activated emergency protocols and sealed three LGAs.",
    time:"1 hr ago", confidence:"Developing",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1576091160550-2173dba999ef?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>The World Health Organization and Nigeria's Centre for Disease Control and Prevention jointly confirmed on Saturday afternoon a novel haemorrhagic fever outbreak in Plateau State that has killed 34 people and infected at least 121 since the first cases were identified 11 days ago. The disease — provisionally named Plateau Haemorrhagic Fever — has a current case fatality rate of 28%, higher than Ebola's historical average, prompting the NCDC to activate its highest-level emergency response protocol.</p><p>Three local government areas — Mangu, Bokkos and Barkin Ladi — have been sealed by security forces, with movement restricted to emergency medical personnel and essential supply deliveries. Approximately 200 people identified as close contacts of confirmed cases have been placed in quarantine at Jos University Teaching Hospital, which has been designated the primary treatment centre.</p><p>Genomic sequencing of viral samples at the NCDC reference laboratory in Abuja suggests the pathogen is a novel bunyavirus strain, potentially related to but distinct from Crimean-Congo haemorrhagic fever. The WHO has deployed a 14-person rapid response team from its regional office in Brazzaville and is coordinating with the US Centers for Disease Control on further characterisation of the virus.</p><p>Health Minister Muhammad Ali Pate said the government is "treating this as a national emergency" and has released ₦4.7 billion in emergency health funds for Plateau State. The minister urged calm among the Nigerian public, emphasising that the outbreak remains geographically contained.</p><p>The affected communities are remote and the outbreak was only detected through Nigeria's strengthened disease surveillance network — a system built partly in response to the COVID-19 pandemic. Public health experts said early detection gives Nigeria a significantly better chance of containment than in previous outbreaks.</p>`,
