    headline:"Pan-African Free Trade Zone Goes Live: 54 Countries Begin Zero-Tariff Trading in Historic Moment",
    snippet:"The African Continental Free Trade Area reached full implementation on Saturday, with all 54 signatory nations removing tariffs on goods. Economists project a $450B boost to African GDP within five years.",
    time:"3 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1547471080-7cc2caa01a7e?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>The African Continental Free Trade Area reached its landmark full implementation milestone on Saturday as all 54 signatory nations simultaneously removed tariffs on the final categories of traded goods, creating the world's largest free trade area by number of member nations and a combined market of 1.4 billion people with aggregate GDP of $3.4 trillion. African Union Commission Chair Moussa Faki Mahamat declared it "the most consequential day for African economic integration since independence."</p><p>Nigeria, which has the continent's largest economy and most populous nation, stands to be among the primary beneficiaries. Nigerian manufacturers — from cement producers to pharmaceutical companies to food processors — now have full zero-tariff access to markets from Cape Town to Cairo without the complex bilateral agreement negotiations that previously required years of negotiation. NACCIMA President John Udeagbala described the moment as "the beginning of Nigeria's transformation from Africa's largest consumer market to Africa's largest supplier."</p><p>Intra-African trade currently represents only 16% of Africa's total trade — compared to 68% in Europe and 59% in Asia — meaning the potential for growth under the AfCFTA is enormous. The United Nations Economic Commission for Africa projects the agreement could boost intra-African trade by 52% by 2030 if implementation remains on track.</p><p>Ethiopia's satellite launch two weeks ago and Kenya's tech sector growth have positioned East Africa as a key beneficiary, while Nigeria, Ghana and Côte d'Ivoire are expected to dominate West African trade flows. South Africa's manufacturing base gives it a competitive advantage in supplying Southern and East Africa.</p><p>The major remaining challenge is infrastructure — roads, ports, power and digital connectivity — without which full trade potential cannot be realised. The AfDB committed a $50 billion infrastructure fund specifically tied to AfCFTA corridors on Saturday.</p>`,
