    time:"6 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1494523716954-dc08e5e57e64?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Statistics South Africa published the country's most encouraging employment data in 15 years on Saturday, revealing that the unemployment rate fell to 29.1% in the first quarter of 2026 — below 30% for the first time since 2011 — driven primarily by the creation of 400,000 new jobs in South Africa's booming renewable energy sector and the rapid expansion of digital services exports. The figure represents a 2.8 percentage point improvement from the 31.9% recorded in Q4 2025.</p><p>The renewable energy jobs come primarily from South Africa's Emergency Power Procurement Programme, which has added over 8,000 megawatts of solar and wind capacity in the past 18 months, requiring massive deployment of installation and maintenance workforces. The digital services sector — call centres, software development, data analytics and business process outsourcing — added 95,000 jobs as South Africa's English-language workforce and improving connectivity attracted contracts from US and UK companies.</p><p>President Cyril Ramaphosa called the data "a vindication of our patient, structural approach to economic reform" but acknowledged that the unemployment rate — while historically improved — remains among the highest for any major economy in the world. Youth unemployment specifically fell from 60.2% to 56.7%, still a deeply troubling figure.</p><p>For Nigeria, South Africa's jobs success story carries lessons about the potential of renewable energy manufacturing and installation as an employment-intensive industry. Energy Minister Adebayo Adelabu cited South Africa's model in defending Nigeria's own accelerated solar procurement programme.</p><p>The Johannesburg Stock Exchange rose 2.3% on the data, with construction, technology and consumer discretionary stocks leading the advance.</p>`,
