    id:"af3", category:"Africa", categorySlug:"africa",
    headline:"Kenya's Nairobi Overtakes Lagos as Africa's Top Tech Startup Destination — $2.1B in VC Funding",
    snippet:"New data shows Nairobi attracted $2.1 billion in venture capital in 2025, edging out Lagos for the first time, as Kenya's regulatory environment and tax incentives draw global tech investors.",
    time:"8 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1512453979798-5ea266f8880c?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Nairobi attracted $2.1 billion in venture capital investment in 2025, surpassing Lagos's $1.87 billion for the first time to become Africa's most funded tech startup ecosystem, according to data published by Partech Africa on Saturday. The ranking marks a significant shift in Africa's tech investment landscape and has triggered sharp debate in Nigeria about whether the country is losing its competitive edge in the continent's most dynamic economic sector.</p><p>Kenya's ascendancy is attributed to several factors: the Kenya Revenue Authority's startup-friendly tax regime which offers five-year tax holidays for qualifying tech companies, the Nairobi International Financial Centre's streamlined licensing processes, a strong pipeline of engineering talent from the University of Nairobi and Strathmore University, and the concentration of major international tech companies — including Google's Africa Product Development hub, Microsoft's Africa Development Centre and Visa's fintech accelerator — all headquartered in Nairobi.</p><p>Nigerian tech sector leaders reacted with a mixture of alarm and competitiveness. Flutterwave CEO Olugbenga Agboola posted a LinkedIn thread challenging the Nigerian government to match Kenya's regulatory improvements, listing seven specific policy changes he said would restore Lagos's top position within 18 months. Paystack, Interswitch and PiggyVest executives signed a joint open letter to the Federal Ministry of Communications calling for urgent action.</p><p>Lagos State Governor Sanwo-Olu announced a ₦50 billion Lagos Tech Competitiveness Fund the same day, designed to provide low-interest loans to qualifying tech startups and attract international VC firms to establish offices in Lagos.</p><p>Partech's report noted that despite Kenya's lead in total funding, Nigeria still produces Africa's highest number of tech unicorns — companies valued at over $1 billion — suggesting that while investment has shifted, Nigeria's ecosystem depth remains formidable.</p>`,
