    headline:"8 Platforms Paying Nigerians $15-$80/Hour for Remote Work Right Now — March 2026",
    snippet:"With the naira at ₦1,580/$1, earning in dollars is no longer optional for millions of Nigerians. These 8 platforms are actively hiring Nigerians for remote work this week.",
    time:"2 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1499750310107-5fef28a66643?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>With the naira trading at a record ₦1,580 to the US dollar this week, earning even a few hundred dollars monthly has become the difference between surviving and thriving for millions of Nigerian professionals. NRT has verified eight platforms that are actively accepting Nigerian applicants and paying in hard currency in March 2026 — not theoretical future opportunities but platforms with open roles right now.</p><p>Scale AI remains the most accessible entry point, paying $15-$28 per hour for AI training tasks that require no specialist qualifications beyond strong written English — content review, data labelling, and AI response evaluation. Payments are made via Payoneer weekly. Appen offers similar work at $12-$22 per hour through its Crowd platform. Both platforms have open applications with same-week onboarding for qualified candidates.</p><p>For software engineers and developers, Toptal continues to offer the highest rates — $60-$200 per hour for the top 3% of applicants who clear its rigorous screening process. Andela, which now places African engineers with US and European companies through a managed staffing model, is currently recruiting specifically for React, Node.js and Python engineers with two or more years of experience. Monthly retainers range from $2,000 to $6,000.</p><p>Content creators and writers should look at Contently and ClearVoice, both of which pay $0.25-$1.00 per word for freelance content. At ₦1,580 per dollar, a 2,000-word article paying $350 earns ₦553,000 — more than many Nigerian professionals earn monthly. Both platforms require a portfolio review but typically make decisions within one week.</p><p>For educators, Coursera's instructor programme and Udemy's platform are actively seeking Nigerians with expertise in accounting, law, Yoruba/Hausa/Igbo language instruction, traditional medicine, and agricultural science — areas where Nigerian expertise is genuinely scarce globally. Revenue shares on popular courses can reach $5,000-$15,000 monthly for high-quality content.</p>`,
