    id:"m2", category:"Money", categorySlug:"money",
    headline:"Flutterwave Launches 'DollarSave' — Nigerian App That Automatically Invests Spare Change in USD",
    snippet:"Flutterwave's new DollarSave product converts naira transactions into dollar-denominated savings automatically, offering Nigerians a hedge against currency depreciation from as little as ₦1,000.",
    time:"5 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1559526324-593bc073d938?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Flutterwave launched DollarSave on Saturday — a financial product that automatically converts a user-defined percentage of every naira transaction into dollar-denominated savings, giving ordinary Nigerians a systematic hedge against naira depreciation without requiring any financial sophistication or large upfront investment. The minimum starting amount is ₦1,000, deliberately set to be accessible to the widest possible income range.</p><p>The product works by connecting to a user's bank accounts via open banking APIs and automatically sweeping a chosen percentage — the default is 5%, but users can set between 1% and 50% — of every incoming transaction into a dollar-denominated savings account that earns 4.2% annual interest. The dollars are purchased at the NAFEM official rate, providing a buffer against the parallel market premium.</p><p>Flutterwave CEO Olugbenga Agboola described DollarSave as "the product I wished existed when I was a young professional watching the naira erode my savings year after year." He said the product had 45,000 beta users during its test phase and that over ₦2.1 billion had already been converted to dollar savings in the beta period.</p><p>For context: a Nigerian who had converted ₦500,000 to dollars in January 2024 when the rate was ₦1,100 would now hold the equivalent of ₦718,000 — a 43.6% return on a product that required zero active investment decisions. This kind of passive dollarisation has become increasingly discussed in middle-class Nigerian financial planning circles.</p><p>The Central Bank of Nigeria confirmed that DollarSave operates within existing regulatory frameworks and that Flutterwave holds the appropriate licenses for the product. Privacy advocates raised questions about the extent of transaction data access required, which Flutterwave said it would address in a forthcoming transparency report.</p>`,
