    snippet:"Google DeepMind opened its African headquarters in Yaba, Lagos on Saturday, marking the largest single international tech investment in Nigerian history with 500 direct research jobs.",
    time:"4 hrs ago", confidence:"Verified",
    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1677442135703-1787eea5ce01?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>Google opened the DeepMind Africa Research Centre in Yaba, Lagos on Saturday morning in a ceremony attended by President Tinubu, Google CEO Sundar Pichai and DeepMind CEO Demis Hassabis — marking the single largest international technology investment in Nigerian history at $200 million, creating 500 direct research positions and expected to catalyse a further $800 million in related investment over five years.</p><p>The 18,000 square metre facility in the heart of Yaba's tech district will house research teams working on AI applications specifically designed for African contexts: malaria and tuberculosis detection, crop disease identification, infrastructure optimisation for unreliable power grids, and natural language processing for African languages including Yoruba, Hausa, Igbo, Swahili and Amharic.</p><p>Google CEO Sundar Pichai, speaking at the opening, said Africa represented "the most exciting frontier for AI's potential to solve real human problems at scale" and committed that the centre's research would be shared openly with African universities and governments. He announced a $50 million scholarship fund for African AI researchers, providing full funding for PhD programmes at leading global universities with a requirement to return to Africa and work on African challenges for at least three years.</p><p>For Nigeria's tech ecosystem, the DeepMind presence is expected to have compounding effects: talent that might previously have migrated to the US or UK to work on frontier AI will now have world-class opportunities in Lagos; Nigerian universities will gain access to cutting-edge research partnerships; and the centre's presence will attract other major tech companies evaluating African expansion.</p><p>Governor Sanwo-Olu announced a 10-year property tax holiday for qualifying AI and deep-tech companies establishing research operations in Lagos in a package designed to maximise the multiplier effect of the DeepMind anchor investment.</p>`,
