    image:"https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1455390582262-044cdead277a?w=900&q=80",
    body:`<p>When the naira struck ₦1,580 to the US dollar on Saturday morning, the instinctive narrative in official circles was familiar: global headwinds, oil price volatility, speculative attacks, the weight of history. These factors are real. They are also, in large measure, excuses for choices that Nigeria's economic leadership has made and continues to make that have systematically undermined the naira's foundations for decades.</p><p>Let us be specific about those choices. First: Nigeria earns dollars primarily through crude oil exports but has, for fifty years, refused to develop a domestic refining industry of meaningful scale. The result is that we spend more importing refined petroleum products than we earn from selling crude — a structurally suicidal arrangement that the Dangote Refinery is only beginning to address. Second: our non-oil export sector is less than 5% of GDP, meaning a single commodity's price fluctuations determine the fate of 220 million people's purchasing power. Third: the CBN has repeatedly allowed politically connected actors to exploit the gap between official and parallel market rates — a subsidy to the well-connected paid for by every ordinary Nigerian who buys imported goods.</p><p>None of these are natural phenomena. They are policy choices with identifiable authors. The Tinubu administration deserves credit for removing the fuel subsidy — a genuinely difficult political decision — but removing one subsidy while preserving FX arbitrage opportunities is like treating one symptom while ignoring the underlying disease.</p><p>The solutions are not mysterious: export diversification through the kind of industrial policy that has transformed South Korea, Taiwan and Malaysia; aggressive development of the non-oil export sector; genuine FX market transparency that eliminates arbitrage opportunities; and sustained investment in the infrastructure — power, transport, logistics — that makes non-oil exports competitive. These require sustained political will across multiple government cycles. They are not impossible. They are choices.</p>`,
